          "id": "psychology-101-l02-c1",
          "title": "Neurons and Synaptic Transmission",
          "content": "The human nervous system is a fascinating and complex network that plays a crucial role in how we think, feel, and behave. It is made up of approximately 86 billion neurons, which are specialized cells responsible for transmitting information throughout our bodies. Each neuron is connected to thousands of other neurons, leading to an astonishing total of around 100 trillion synapses in the brain. This vast network allows for the rapid communication of signals that underlie all our mental processes.\nNeurons have three main parts that work together to send messages. The first part is called dendrites, which are like tiny branches that receive signals from other neurons. The second part is the cell body, also known as the soma, which processes the information it receives. Finally, there is the axon, which is a long, thin structure that transmits signals to other neurons. Many axons are covered by a protective layer called the myelin sheath. This sheath acts like insulation on a wire, helping to speed up the transmission of signals through a process known as saltatory conduction.\nWhen a neuron receives enough stimulation and reaches a certain threshold, it generates an electrical impulse known as an action potential. This impulse travels down the axon at incredible speeds, reaching up to 120 meters per second! When the action potential reaches the end of the axon, it arrives at the synapse, which is the tiny gap between two neurons. Here, the electrical signal triggers the release of chemical messengers called neurotransmitters. These neurotransmitters then cross the synaptic cleft, the space between neurons, and bind to receptors on the next neuron, allowing the signal to continue its journey.\nThis intricate electrochemical process happens billions of times every second and is essential for everything we do, from thinking and feeling to moving and reacting. Understanding how neurons and synapses work helps us appreciate the complexity of our brains and the amazing capabilities they provide us with every day.\nContext recap: The human nervous system is a fascinating and complex network that plays a crucial role in how we think, feel, and behave. It is made up of approximately 86 billion neurons, which are specialized cells responsible for transmitting information throughout our bodies. Each neuron is connected to thousands of other neurons, leading to an astonishing total of around 100 trillion synapses in the brain. This vast network allows for the rapid communication of signals that underlie all our mental processes.\nWhy this matters: Neurons and Synaptic Transmission helps learners in Psychology connect ideas from Introduction to Psychology to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints."
